Disk Forensics > [T9]: Windows SRUM: Tracking System Resource Usage

(9) SRUM (System Resource Usage Monitor)

The Windows System Resource Usage Monitor (SRUM) is a feature that was introduced in Windows 8. It tracks system resource usage, such as application resource usage, energy usage, Windows push notifications, network connectivity, and data usage, for a period of 30 to 60 days. SRUM is enabled by default and configured to start automatically when the system starts up. Some of the data collected by SRUM is available to the user through the "App history" tab on the Task Manager in Windows 8 and later versions. However, the database associated with SRUM contains a large amount of additional information that is not visible to the user.

The information included in the SRUM database can be viewed by the normal user using Taskmanager. 

 

Resource Monitor GUI

You can use "SrumECmd" to analyze the SRUM database located at "C:\Windows\System32\sru", but before proceeding with the analysis, check first if  "SRUDB.dat" need to be repaired.

  1. The "Face Time" field in the SRUM database refers to the amount of time that an application was actively being used by the user. This may be helpful in understanding what the most actively used applications by the user are. It can also help spot odd applications that have been used for a very limited time.
